(27377, 293071, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1434626013;s:7:"mytitle";s:13:"Primal Colors";s:6:"mylink";s:51:"http://www.irrawaddy.org/culture/primal-colors.html";s:6:"mydesc";s:1243:"<a href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/culture/primal-colors.html#gallery-84670-1-slideshow">Click to view slideshow.</a>\n<p>RANGOON &mdash; Simplicity is the defining motif of renowned Burmese painter MPP Yei Myint&rsquo;s latest solo show.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;The best things I like are the simplest things,&rdquo; the 62-year old artist said at Think Art Gallery in downtown Rangoon, where his seventh solo show, &lsquo;Origin&rsquo;, is running from June 17 to 19.</p>\n<p>Drawn from the last eight years of his oeuvre, the 67 paintings on display this week rely heavily on primary colors and austere, geometrical compositions&mdash;a striking contrast from the bold styles and ominous shadows in the work of &lsquo;Cancer&rsquo;, his 2014 exhibition which chronicled the social ills plaguing Burma.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s up to the viewers to decide whether they like them or not,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;For me, I think we need to make changes sometimes.&rdquo;</p>\n<p><em>Think Art Gallery is located at 231 Nawaday Street, Dagon Township.</em></p>\n<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/culture/primal-colors.html">Primal Colors</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/">The Irrawaddy</a>.</p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:3:"T G";s:12:"itemcategory";s:46:"Arts, A_Factiva, Burma, Culture, THE IRRAWADDY";s:7:"mycatid";s:1:"2";s:7:"myGroup";s:13:"The Irrawaddy";s:6:"feedID";i:53149;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
