(31434, 294081, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1434753300;s:7:"mytitle";s:73:"Myanmar Students Vow Continued Reform Push After Passage of Education Law";s:6:"mylink";s:66:"http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/reform-06192015175225.html";s:6:"mydesc";s:3808:"<img src="http://www.rfa.org/english/news/myanmar/government-agrees-to-student-demands-02112015173400.html/myanmar-student-protestors-yangon-feb8-2015.jpg"><p>Myanmar&rsquo;s Union Parliament on Thursday voted into law a controversial bill for education reform, angering student activists who said the law in its amended form has failed to include key provisions they believed had been agreed to in government-sponsored talks.</p>\r\n<p>The now-enacted National Education Law &ldquo;is very different, both in concept and essence&rdquo; from the 11 demands student leaders thought they had won in four-way discussions earlier this year with government representatives, lawmakers, and education reform advocates, one student activist told RFA&rsquo;s Myanmar Service on Thursday.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The government and parliament refused to approve the draft law that included student demands presented in the talks,&rdquo; said Aung Nay Paing, a leader of Democracy Education Initiative Committee, which had participated in the talks.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;They have broken their promises and agreements,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p>Student demands had included a secure role for student unions in forming education policy, though the law now cites only participation by &ldquo;student representatives,&rdquo; Aung Nay Paing said, adding that the new law simply strengthens government control.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;This puts student unions on a level with other, ordinary social organizations,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;It shouldn&rsquo;t be like this.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Education reform advocate Thein Lwin of the National Network for Education Reform (NNER), quoted in <i>The Irrawaddy</i> on Thursday, meanwhile called for a stronger role for student unions across the country.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Considering Burma&rsquo;s university history, we need to enhance the role of student unions, which had [existed] until 1962&rdquo; when they were abolished following a military coup, Lwin said.</p>\r\n<p><b>Continued push for reform</b></p>\r\n<p>Other demands proposed by students and reformers include a decentralized education system; changes to university entrance exams; modernization of the national curriculum; the provision of free, compulsory education through Grade 9; and the guarantee of &ldquo;mother tongue instruction&rdquo; in the language of Myanmar&rsquo;s ethnic minorities in the lower grades.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Under the current system of &lsquo;English and Burmese as the medium [of] instruction, students are taught almost exclusively in Burmese at government schools&mdash;a system that does not look likely to change&nbsp; under the amended law,&rdquo; <i>The Irrawaddy</i> said.</p>\r\n<p>In a move likely to win reformers'' support, one provision of the new law promises to "set a target to use 20 percent of the state budget for education spending" in response to earlier demands,<i> The Irrawaddy</i> said.</p>\r\n<p>Aung Nay Paing said that his group will continue to push for reform.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We didn&rsquo;t get what we wanted, but we will hold a meeting with the Democracy Education Initiative Committee&rsquo;s members and discuss exactly what we are going to do next.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>In May, more than 70 student activists meanwhile went on trial in a court in central Myanmar to face unlawful assembly and rioting charges stemming from a protest calling for education reform.</p>\r\n<p>Most were among the 127 arrested two months before during a violent police crackdown on student-led peaceful protests in the central town of Letpadan in the Tharrawaddy district of the country''s Bago division, where they had stopped en route to a cross-country march to the commercial capital Yangon.</p>\r\n<p><i><b>Reported by RFA&rsquo;s Myanmar Service. Translated by Khet Mar. Written in English by Richard Finney.</b></i></p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";s:17:"education, reform";s:7:"mycatid";s:1:"2";s:7:"myGroup";s:23:"Radio Free Asia Myanmar";s:6:"feedID";i:53271;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
