(33186, 294516, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1427896569;s:7:"mytitle";s:35:"Potential Benefits Drive AEC Engine";s:6:"mylink";s:61:"http://www.aseannews.net/potential-benefits-drive-aec-engine/";s:6:"mydesc";s:4226:"<p>By Seulki Lee</p>\n<p><strong>BANGKOK</strong>, Mar 31 &ndash; What speeds up the process of ASEAN integration the most? Academics, government officials, business people, and economists around the region share the same answer: the potential economic incentives from the creation of a single regional market and production base.<span></span></p>\n<p>This is the reason why the ASEAN Economic Community (AEC) gets the biggest share of the media spotlight, compared to the two other pillars of ASEAN community &ndash; the political-security and the socio-cultural ones.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;Compared to the European model, ASEAN regional integration shows three characteristics. It is very much market-driven, (it is) a very slim outfit (institutional) by design, and very much engaged with trading partners out of the region,&rdquo; Jayant Menon, lead economist for regional integration of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, told the forum attended by some 120 participants.</p>\n<p>According to the Malaysian economist, the most happening trend in ASEAN integration is the emergence of a regional supply chain, the &lsquo;ASEAN factory&rsquo;. &ldquo;The rhetoric that goes with AEC doesn&rsquo;t compromise the commitment of openness that has defined ASEAN over the years. We are nine months away to the deadline. According to ASEAN, we completed 80 percent to reach AEC. But we should remember this is not the destination, but a journey,&rdquo; Menon pointed out.</p>\n<p>&ldquo;The real challenge facing AEC is how these agreements are implemented in the end,&rdquo; he said, including those providing for mutual recognition arrangements to allow (the movement of) skilled labour in ASEAN and a monetary mechanism in ASEAN.</p>\n<p>For his part, Carl Middleton, a lecturer at Chulalongkorn University, Thailand, says attention needs to be paid to companies&rsquo; cross-border accountability as integration encourages them to do more business regionally. &ldquo;The question is how can justice be served cross-border when the ASEAN economy is integrated?&rdquo; he asked.</p>\n<p>Carl introduced &ldquo;corporate accountability&rdquo;, a new norm that many might confuse with the philanthropic approach of corporate social responsibility (CSR). Corporate accountability addresses human rights violations in the context of business activities on the national, regional and international levels. While the AEC Blueprint outlines ASEAN&rsquo;s strategy for economic integration, promoting CSR is incorporated separately into the ASEAN Socio-Cultural Community Blueprint. &ldquo;Is CSR enough? CSR would be welcome, but there is a need to go beyond that to ensure that business activity is accountable,&rdquo; Middleton pointed out.</p>\n<p>Stressing the need to build upon existing mechanisms for extra-territorial obligations, he shared two case studies from Khon Kaen sugar company in Koh Kong province of Cambodia and the Xayaburi dam project in lower Mekong mainstream, northern Laos. While the Khon Kaen case was an issue between Cambodia and Thailand, the Xayaburi dam was an issue for Laos, Cambodia, and Vietnam. These two examples showed how cross-border corporate activities could violate the multiple rights of communities in ASEAN, he said.</p>\n<p>For his part, Umesh Pandey, editor of the &lsquo;Asia Focus&rsquo; section of the &lsquo;Bangkok Post&rsquo; newspaper, said covering AEC and related issues brought up the two challenges of language and accessibility to sources. &ldquo;One of the biggest problems in this region is English skills. Good people (journalists) are there in Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia, but in their native languages,&rdquo; said Pandey. &ldquo;Accessibility to government sources is another difficulty, while companies are willing to talk about their ongoing businesses.&rdquo;</p>\n<p>For Pandey, there are challenges to covering the ASEAN economic integration process beyond borders. &ldquo;I can be good about Thai issues on ASEAN business and economy, but not about other ASEAN countries&rsquo;,&rdquo; he explained. On some stories, &ldquo;there are limited topics to write&rdquo;, he added.&nbsp;&nbsp; For Laos, he said, &ldquo;It&rsquo;s always forestry and dams. Brunei, it&rsquo;s</p>";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:9:"Admin IPS";s:12:"itemcategory";s:65:"Features, Reporting ASEAN: 2015 and Beyond Series, The ASEAN Beat";s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53203;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
