(33278, 294539, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1430406805;s:7:"mytitle";s:55:"Indonesia’s foreign policy: A thousand jilted friends";s:6:"mylink";s:123:"http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21650173-new-president-charts-markedly-different-course-thousand-jilted-friends?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1424:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Who should govern Britain?        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Indonesia&rsquo;s foreign policy        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The new president charts a markedly different course        \n        \n\n\n\n\n      Location:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    JAKARTA        \n        \n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Jokowi the enforcer        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\nJokowi the enforcer\n\nWHEN Joko Widodo came to power last year, he promised to be decisive and to stand up for Indonesia. On April 29th he seemed to fulfil both promises when Indonesia went ahead with the executions of eight convicted drug-smugglers, all but one of them foreign (see article).\nTheir fates, which hung on the pen of the president, have strained Indonesia&rsquo;s foreign relations. Australia has snapped, withdrawing its ambassador, for now (see article). The executions may throw light on how Jokowi, as he is known, intends to conduct his foreign policy. If so, he risks damage to Indonesia&rsquo;s international standing. Only a few months ago, pundits said the chief risk under Jokowi was that handling foreign ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53182;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
