(33322, 294550, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1400165953;s:7:"mytitle";s:26:"Banyan: Getting in the way";s:6:"mylink";s:136:"http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21602265-south-east-asia-finds-decorum-its-regional-club-rather-rudely-shattered-getting-way?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1418:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Europe goes to the polls        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Banyan        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    South-East Asia finds the decorum of its regional club rather rudely shattered        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20140517_ASD000_0.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTHE ten-member Association of South-East Asian Nations is proud of how it does things. &ldquo;The ASEAN way&rdquo; favours consensus over confrontation, conviviality over candour and process over substance. It is credited with keeping the peace in what was once a strife-torn region. And co-operation within ASEAN not only enhances its economic coherence and attractiveness to outsiders, but also gives it a diplomatic clout its individual members could never attain. Yet as its leaders met on May 10th and 11th for a summit in Naypyidaw, the capital of Myanmar, ASEAN&rsquo;s achievements seemed under threat on all fronts.\nThe meeting was overshadowed by a confrontation in the South China Sea between Vietnam, an ASEAN member, and China. In one of the most dangerous of many stand-offs between China and other ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53182;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
