(33350, 294557, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1353600181;s:7:"mytitle";s:36:"America in Asia: On the rocks, again";s:6:"mylink";s:117:"http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21567108-barack-obama-courts-region-odds-over-south-china-sea-rocks-again?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1444:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Old battles, new Middle East        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    America in Asia        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Barack Obama courts a region at odds over the South China Sea        \n        \n\n\n\n\n      Location:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    BANGKOK AND PHNOM PENH         \n        \n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The smiles come as naturally as the shirts        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\nThe smiles come as naturally as the shirts\n\nIF ONE word sums up the style of the ten-member Association of South-East Asian Nations (ASEAN), it is &ldquo;consensus&rdquo;. So when its meeting in Cambodia in July ended in open disagreement, many assumed it was an aberration. But even at the highlight of ASEAN&rsquo;s calendar, the series of summits in Phnom Penh between November 18th and 20th, including the 18-member East Asia Summit, the group could not present a united front. A row erupted again over the same issue&mdash;how to manage China&rsquo;s territorial claims in the South China Sea&mdash;and between the same ASEAN protagonists, the Philippines and Cambodia. ASEAN seems divided as never before, some ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53182;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
