(33370, 294562, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1431011228;s:7:"mytitle";s:40:"Indonesia’s economy: Spicing up growth";s:6:"mylink";s:138:"http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21650586-bad-policy-much-bad-infrastructure-holding-indonesia-back-spicing-up?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1469:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    The dawn of artificial intelligence        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Indonesia&rsquo;s economy        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Bad policy as much as bad infrastructure is holding Indonesia back        \n        \n\n\n\n\n      Location:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    JAKARTA        \n        \n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20150509_FNP001_0.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nIN LATE April Indonesia&rsquo;s president, Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, wooed foreign moneymen at a big international conference. Investing in Indonesia will bring &ldquo;incredible profits&rdquo;, he promised. &ldquo;And if you have any problems, call me.&rdquo; Two days later, at a summit of Asian and African dignitaries, Jokowi struck a different note. He called for &ldquo;a new global economic order that is open to new emerging economic powers&rdquo; to avoid the &ldquo;domination of certain groups and countries&rdquo;.\nThat is not necessarily a contradiction: you can pursue foreign cash while also arguing that international financial institutions grant developing countries too little power. But the change in tone was striking: from ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53171;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
