(33386, 294566, 'rssmi_item_description', 'a:1:{i:0;a:11:{s:9:"mystrdate";i:1428590689;s:7:"mytitle";s:33:"Banyan: Where all Silk Roads lead";s:6:"mylink";s:134:"http://www.economist.com/news/china/21648039-through-fog-hazy-slogans-contours-chinas-vision-asia-emerge-where-all-silk-roads?fsrc=rss";s:6:"mydesc";s:1461:"UK Only Article:&amp;nbsp;\n                    standard article        \n        \n\n\n\n      Issue:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    What does Hillary stand for?        \n        \n\n\n\n      Fly Title:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Banyan        \n        \n\n\n\n      Rubric:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    Through a fog of hazy slogans, the contours of China&rsquo;s vision for Asia emerge        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n      Main image:&amp;nbsp;\n    \n            \n                    20150411_CND000_0.jpg        \n        \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNOT content with both purifying the Chinese Communist Party which he heads and with reforming his country, China&rsquo;s president, Xi Jinping, also wants to reshape the economic and political order in Asia. With the flair that Chinese leaders share for pithy but rather bewildering encapsulations, his vision for the continent is summed up in official jargon as &ldquo;One Belt, One Road&rdquo;. As Mr Xi describes it, most recently last month at the Boao Forum, China&rsquo;s tropical-beach imitation of Davos&rsquo;s ski slopes, the belt-road concept will &ldquo;answer the call of our time for regional and global co-operation&rdquo;. Not everybody is convinced. Some see it as no more than an empty slogan; others as a thinly disguised Chinese plot to supplant America as Asia&rsquo;s predominant power. Both criticisms seem misplaced. Mr Xi ...&lt;div class="og_rss_groups"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;";s:7:"myimage";N;s:8:"myAuthor";s:0:"";s:12:"itemcategory";N;s:7:"mycatid";N;s:7:"myGroup";N;s:6:"feedID";i:53171;s:13:"useMediaImage";i:0;}}'),
