(47319, 8, '2014-03-21 10:27:32', '2014-03-21 03:27:32', '<!--:en--><h3>Overview and prospects</h3>\n[caption id="attachment_47372" align="alignright" width="584"]<a href="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Nam-Ngouang-Dam-in-Laos.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-47372" alt="Nam Ngouang Dam in Laos (by Eric Banar, 2011 for WorldFish)" src="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Nam-Ngouang-Dam-in-Laos-1024x682.jpg" width="584" height="388" /></a> Nam Ngouang Dam in Laos (by Eric Banar, 2011 for WorldFish)[/caption]\n<p style="text-align: left">According to the Asian Development Bank, expanding the interconnection of Greater Mekong Subregion power systems would generate savings of $14.3 billion from 2010 to 2030, mainly by replacing the use of fossil fuels with hydropower. Better interconnection of power systems in the region will allow savings through conversion from fossil fuel systems to hydroelectric ones, thus lowering carbon emissions as well.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left">ADB’s updated master plan for the region will focus on interconnection projects for large-scale power exchanges between hydro-rich nations (Laos, Myanmar, and to a lesser extent Cambodia) and thermal-dominated importing nations (Thailand and Vietnam). Hydro-powered nations will become the key energy exporters of the Greater Mekong Subregion, with a combined 44 GW hydro potential at a cost lower than $100/MWh. This will benefit the export countries in their development of electrification, lowered costs for electricity, and additional cash resources for development.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left">In particular, the tri-border area between Laos, Cambodia, and Vietnam has several possible interconnections for energy development. This is due to the quantity and geographic proximity of hydro projects in the southern Laos and Cambodia compared to load areas in central /southern Vietnam.</p>\n<p style="text-align: left">Sources: ADB 2010 Update of the GMS Regional Master Plan; Southeast Asia Infrastructure magazine</p>\n\n<h3>Organizations and Initiatives</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li><a style="font-style: normal" title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/">Mekong River Commission Initiative on Sustainable Hydropower</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://mekong.waterandfood.org/cpwf-mekong">CGIAR Challenge Program on Water and Food</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.terraper.org/mainpage/index_en.php?langs=en">Foundation for Ecological Recovery</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/mekong-mainstream-dams">International Rivers Mekong Mainstream Dams campaign</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://www.savethemekong.org/">Save the Mekong</a></li>\n</ul>\n<!--span style="color: #333333; font-family: ''Helvetica Neue'', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; line-height: 1.625;"-->\n<h3>Data</h3>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>Dataset compiled from various sources: <a style="font-style: normal" title="https://github.com/OpenDevelopmentCambodia/geospatial/blob/master/mekong-hydro-map.csv" href="https://github.com/OpenDevelopmentCambodia/geospatial/blob/master/mekong-hydro-map.csv">https://github.com/OpenDevelopmentCambodia/geospatial/blob/master/mekong-hydro-map.csv</a></li>\n	<li><a style="font-style: normal" title="http://mekong.waterandfood.org/archives/2648" href="http://mekong.waterandfood.org/archives/2648">Map of hydropower and reservoirs in the Mekong Basin</a>, CGIAR Challenge Program on Water and Food (geospatial file also available)</li>\n	<li><a title="http://www.themimu.info/sites/themimu.info/files/documents/Sector%20Map_EcoInfra_Population2011-HydropowerLocation_MIMU955v01_22Jan13_A4.pdf" href="http://www.themimu.info/sites/themimu.info/files/documents/Sector%20Map_EcoInfra_Population2011-HydropowerLocation_MIMU955v01_22Jan13_A4.pdf" target="_blank">2011 population density and hydropower location (Myanmar)</a>, Myanmar Information Management Unit (PDF)</li>\n	<li><a style="font-style: normal" title="http://www.gms-eoc.org/gis-data?cat=7" href="http://www.gms-eoc.org/gis-data?cat=7">GMS rivers and basins geospatial data</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Laws and agreements<!--/span--></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>1995 <a title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/agreements/95-agreement.pdf" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/agreements/95-agreement.pdf">Agreement on the Cooperation for the Sustainable Development of the Mekong River Basin</a> (signed by Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, and Vietnam)</li>\n</ul>\n<!--span style="color: #333333; font-family: ''Helvetica Neue'', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; line-height: 1.625;"-->\n<h3>Documents</h3>\n[dg]<a href="http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/IR-Don-Sahong-fact-sheet-Sept-2008.pdf">\n</a>\n\n<a style="font-style: normal" title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/">MRC Strategic Environmental Assessment of Mainstream Dams</a>\n\n<a style="font-style: normal" title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/sea-stakeholder-submissions/" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/sea-stakeholder-submissions/">SEA Stakeholder Submissions</a>\n\n<a style="font-style: normal" title="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/sea-petitions-and-mrc-responses/" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/about-the-mrc/programmes/initiative-on-sustainable-hydropower/strategic-environmental-assessment-of-mainstream-dams/sea-petitions-and-mrc-responses/">SEA petitions and MRC responses</a>\n\n<!--span style="color: #333333; font-family: ''Helvetica Neue'', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 15px; font-style: inherit; font-weight: inherit; line-height: 1.625;"-->\n\n<!--/div-->\n<!--div id="magicdomid40"--><!--/div--><!--:-->', 'Hydropower', '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', 'hydropower-2', '', '', '2014-03-21 10:27:32', '2014-03-21 03:27:32', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/?page_id=47319', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(47400, 8, '2014-03-25 10:32:23', '2014-03-25 03:32:23', '<!--:en-->It''s a brave new world of data! Wondering how to make sense of it all? The data in our catalog comes in a variety of formats, with a preference for those that those that are widely usable and both human and machine readable. We seek to provide accurate metadata, which allows users to better understand the available data. Datasets can be directly downloaded from our site and, eventually, we aim to provide an API.\n\nIf you are curious to learn more about the file formats you may encounter, the structure of the metadata, how to get the data, and some advice for conducting your own analyses, do read on.\n<h2>File Formats</h2>\n<strong>CSV (Comma-Separated Value)</strong> • A tabular (spreadsheet) data format, where the column values are separated by commas. CSV files are both human and machine readable. They can be opened in many applications, including Excel, OpenOffice and Google Docs.\n\n<strong>GeoJSON</strong> • <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JSON">JSON</a> (or JavaScript Object Notation) is an easily human and machine readable open standard format, which transmits data objects consisting of attribute-value pairs. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GeoJSON">GeoJSON</a> is an extension of JSON that allows for the encoding of simple geographical features (points, lines and polygons) along with non-spatial attributes. GeoJSON files can be opened by desktop applications such as TileMill, QGIS, ArcGIS, and RStudio. In addition, they can be visualized with online tools such as <a href="http://geojson.io/">GeoJSON.io</a>, <a href="https://github.com/blog/1528-there-s-a-map-for-that">GitHub</a>, and <a href="https://github.com/blog/1576-gist-meets-geojson">Gist</a>.\n\n<strong>GeoTIFF </strong>• <em>To fill.</em>\n\n<strong>JPEG</strong> • <em>To fill.</em>\n\n<strong>KML</strong> • <em>To fill.</em>\n\n<strong>PNG</strong> • <em>To fill.</em>\n\n<strong>SHP (ESRI Shapefile)</strong> • Shapefiles are one of the most common geospatial formats out there. Like GeoJSON, shapefiles can store both spatial geometries (points, lines and polygons) and other feature attributes. In addition to ArcGIS, these files can be opened in free an open source GIS applications like QGIS. They can also be converted to many other data formats. The online utility OGRE supports conversion from SHP and other file formats into GeoJSON.\n\n<strong>TXT (Plain Text)</strong> • <i>To fill.</i>\n<h2>Getting the Data</h2>\n<strong>Direct Download</strong>\n\n<em>To fill.</em>\n\n<em></em><strong>CKAN API</strong>\n\n<em>To fill.</em>\n<h2>Using the Data</h2>\n<strong>Maps</strong>\n<ol>\n	<li>For more information about maps and geospatial data, head to the excellent <a href="http://mapschool.io/">mapschool ''a free introduction to geo''</a>.</li>\n	<li>Next get a deeper understanding of the various ways this information can be encoded with <a href="http://geohackers.in/2013/11/spatial-data-formats-101/">Spatial Data Formats 101</a>.</li>\n	<li>Finally, start to look at some of the many tools for exploring, visualizing, and adding to your data with the <a href="http://maptime.github.io/digitalMapToolKit.html">Maptime! Digital Map Toolkit</a>.</li>\n</ol><!--:-->', 'How to Use the Catalog', '', 'pending', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-use-the-catalog', '', '', '2014-03-25 10:32:23', '2014-03-25 03:32:23', '', 0, 'http://www.opendevelopmentmekong.net/?page_id=47400', 0, 'page', '', 0),
