(61657, 2, '2015-02-06 10:10:21', '2015-02-06 10:10:21', '<!--:en-->\n\nThe Mekong river system with its vast, complex network of tributaries has been identified as a valuable source of hydroelectricity generation and since the 1960s. The Lower Mekong Basin is a key site for large-scale hydropower dam development<sup><a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1">1</a></sup> and it is estimated that it has the potential to generate 30,000 megawatts (MW) of hydropower.<sup><a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2">2</a></sup> Regional <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/government/">governments</a> are considering the construction of 88 dams in the Lower <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">Mekong River basin</a><sup><a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3">3</a></sup> by the year 2030. Over 120 dams are planned for the tributaries and 11 large-scale hydropower dams are slated for the Lower Mekong mainstream, which has the potential to produce over 13,000 MW of hydropower<sup><a href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4">4</a></sup>. While Thailand and Vietnam have already developed most of their tributary sites, Laos; Cambodia and Myanmar currently possess the greatest potential for hydropower resource development, with a combined percentage of hydroelectric generation expected to reach 96 percent in 2030<sup><a href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5">5</a></sup>.\n<h4>Meeting Demand</h4>\nFaced with increasing global <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/energy/">energy</a> prices, along with inflated forecasts in energy demand, countries in the region such as Thailand and Vietnam see hydropower as an attractive, renewable resource that will help meet their exploding energy demands, and diversify their energy mix. For instance, Thailand’s total energy consumption is 80 percent fossil fuel reliant, raising serious questions about the country’s future energy security. For the less-developed host countries of hydropower dams such as Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos, hydropower represents huge <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">foreign direct investment</a> opportunities and the potential for immediate GDP growth fuelled by a rise in electricity export revenues<sup><a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6">6</a></sup>. The Laos government is billing itself as the “battery of Southeast Asia<sup><a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7">7</a></sup>” with 60 generation projects planned for its tributaries and nine on the Mekong mainstream<sup><a href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8">8</a></sup>, which forms a major component of its planned <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">GDP</a> growth of 7% per year<sup><a href="#_edn9" name="_ednref9">9</a></sup>.\n<h4>Large vs. Small Hydropower Dams</h4>\nThere are several types of hydroelectric power plants and they vary in size. The Clean Development Mechanism<sup><a href="#_edn10" name="_ednref10">10</a></sup>, under Article 12 of the Kyoto Protocol, promotes “small” hydropower as a viable alternative to large scale hydropower dams because they are more <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/environment-and-natural-resources/">environmentally sustainable</a> and directly displace greenhouse gas emissions<sup><a href="#_edn11" name="_ednref11">11</a></sup>. The smallest CDM project<sup><a href="#_edn12" name="_ednref12">12</a></sup>, located in Bhutan, has a generation capacity of 0.1MW while the largest is a 1200MW capacity facility in Brazil<sup><a href="#_edn13" name="_ednref13">13</a></sup>. The CDM defines a hydropower project with an output capacity of 15MW or more as “large”, while the European Union defines a large hydropower project as one with an installed capacity greater than 20MW. Unlike large scale projects, small hydropower projects are subjected to fewer regulations and assessments. They often receive less scrutiny, tending to be viewed as individual projects and not seen as part of the cumulative impacts associated with a series or “cascade” of dam projects within any particular region.\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 469px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''Capture Loss to Reservoir gain @ $USD3.00&#047;kg of fish '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;Va&#047;ValueofMekongcapturefisherieslostcomparedtoReservoirfisheriesgained&#047;CaptureLosstoReservoirgainUSD3_00kgoffish&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\n&nbsp;\n<h4>Regional Investment</h4>\n<a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">Economic</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/energy/">energy</a> related security factors have resulted in a trend of “regional bilateralism”<sup><a href="#_edn14" name="_ednref14">14</a></sup>, where key decisions and investment deals regarding hydropower development are largely made outside of international frameworks and instead remain cross-border between the strongest economies in the region (Thailand and Vietnam) and the less industrialized, but resource-rich, economies of Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar.\n\nA range of private investors from banks to multinational companies from China, Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam have formed hybrid private-public partnerships to not only build hydroelectric dams in the Lower Mekong Basin, with the intent to purchase the bulk of that electricity. About 10 percent of the hydropower generated energy will remain in Cambodia and Laos<sup><a href="#_edn15" name="_ednref15">15</a></sup>. China has surpassed the World Bank as the biggest funder of large dams, with about 25,000 dam projects globally, or half the world’s total<sup><a href="#_edn16" name="_ednref16">16</a></sup>. In Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar, China invested more than US$6.1 billion between 2005 and 2011<sup><a href="#_edn17" name="_ednref17">17</a></sup>. To date, much of Cambodia’s hydroelectric power expansion has been financed by Chinese corporations, such as the state-owned Sinhydro – the world’s largest hydropower developer<sup><a href="#_edn18" name="_ednref18">18</a></sup>.\n\nAll the Lower Mekong Basin countries are members of the Mekong River Commission, the only inter-governmental body tasked with facilitating dialogue between all private and public stakeholders in the region related to water governance, which grew out of the 1995 Mekong Agreement<sup><a href="#_edn19" name="_ednref19">19</a></sup>.\n\nDespite these regional processes, no consensus among MRC members needs to be reached for a dam to be planned, approved, or constructed. This fact has led to several trans-boundary disputes between the public-private dam builders and the people and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/government/">governments</a> who are downstream from the hydropower dams and most likely to be affected by their construction.\n\n[wp-feature-box ids="68994"]\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>Environmental Impacts</h4>\nMany of the concerns raised by those opposed to the 11 mainstream hydropower projects are contained in the MRC’s Strategic Environmental Assessment (SEA)<sup><a href="#_edn20" name="_ednref20">20</a></sup>. A critical appraisal of the planned 11 large-scale dams on the Mekong mainstream, the 2010 report outlined key concerns echoed by local and international civil society groups, as well as down-stream governments.\n\nIn weighing the economic benefits against the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/environment-and-natural-resources/">environmental</a> costs and the impacts on <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/social-development/">communities</a>, the key recommendation of the SEA was to defer all mainstream dams for a period of up to ten years, until further studies can be conducted to ensure all stakeholders are informed of the risks. The MRC also warned that the likely costs and benefits of hydropower dams on the Mekong mainstream are likely to be distributed inequitably.\n\nSome of the risks highlighted in the assessment include the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/labor/">livelihoods</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">food security</a> of more than 70% of inhabitants who rely on the fisheries, riverbank gardens, ecotourism ventures, and fertile agricultural lands of the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">Mekong Basin</a> for survival.\n\n<img class="wp-image-67040" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Hydro1.jpg" alt="" width="100%" height="100%" />\n\nIt is projected that the cascade of 11 dams will transform 55% of the Lower Mekong into a chain of stagnant reservoirs, which in turn will inundate the wetlands and terrestrial ecology of the region, almost half of which is recognized as Key Biodiversity Zones, and 5 percent of which is comprised of National Protected Areas and Ramsar sites. The cost of <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">agricultural production</a> lost to dam land inundation was found to be over US$5 million per year, while the increase in the use of fertilizers due to changes in nutrient and sediment trappings would result in a further US$24 million per year. The MRC report states that the irrigation schemes proposed to mitigate these impacts would generate US$15 million per year, resulting in a net <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economic</a> loss in agricultural production<sup><a href="#_edn21" name="_ednref21">21</a></sup>.\n\nDue to changes in the Mekong River’s flow and habitat, around 100 species are at risk, including the already critically endangered Irrawaddy dolphin and the Giant Mekong Catfish, which could be driven to extinction. The loss of 26-42 percent of fish stocks is estimated to cost the region US$500 million per year, and threatens the food security of millions of people in the Lower Mekong Basin who rely on those stocks for food and income. Such an outcome could exacerbate growing inequalities in these developing economies and undermine national <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/social-development/">poverty alleviation</a> goals.\n\n[wp-feature-box ids="69383"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177280"]\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>References</h4>\n<a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1</a>. International Rivers, ‘Mekong Mainstream Dams Campaign’, <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/mekong-mainstream-dams">http://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/mekong-mainstream-dams</a>; <a href="http://www.water-alternatives.org/index.php/volume3/v3issue2/95-a3-2-18/file">http://www.water-alternatives.org/index.php/volume3/v3issue2/95-a3-2-18/file</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2</a>. This does not include China and the Mekong’s hydropower potential within its borders, also termed the Upper Mekong and known as the Lancang in China. It’s capacity is said to be 23,000 MW.\n\n<a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">2</a>. Pittock, J. 2014, “Devil’s Bargain? Hydropower vs. Food Trade-Offs in the Mekong Basin”, World Rivers Review Volume 29, pp.3 <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/node/8456">http://www.internationalrivers.org/node/8456</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">3</a>. <a href="http://mekongriver.info/hydropower">http://mekongriver.info/hydropower</a> (2010)\n\n<a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5</a>. Roberts, D. ‘No More Dams on the Mekong’, New York Times, dated September 23, 2014, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/opinion/no-more-dams-on-the-mekong.html?_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article">http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/opinion/no-more-dams-on-the-mekong.html?_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6</a>. <a href="http://mekongriver.info/hydropower">http://mekongriver.info/hydropower</a> (2010)\n\n<a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7</a>. Pittock, J. 2014, “Devil’s Bargain? Hydropower vs. Food Trade-Offs in the Mekong Basin”, World Rivers Review Volume 29, pp.3 <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/node/8456">http://www.internationalrivers.org/node/8456</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8</a>. <a href="http://splash.abc.net.au/media/-/m/526435/power-is-money-on-the-the-mekong">http://splash.abc.net.au/media/-/m/526435/power-is-money-on-the-the-mekong</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9">9</a>. <a href="http://unfccc.int/kyoto_protocol/mechanisms/clean_development_mechanism/items/2718.php">http://unfccc.int/kyoto_protocol/mechanisms/clean_development_mechanism/items/2718.php</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref10" name="_edn10">10</a>. Purohit, P, 2008, ‘Small hydro power projects under clean development mechanism in India: A preliminary assessment’, Volume 36, Issue 6, June 2008, Pages 2000–2015 <a href="http://www.iiasa.ac.at/publication/more_XJ-08-066.php">http://www.iiasa.ac.at/publication/more_XJ-08-066.php</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref11" name="_edn11">11</a>. <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/120228_hydro-power-brief_lr_web.pdf">http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/120228_hydro-power-brief_lr_web.pdf</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref12" name="_edn12">12</a>. <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/120228_hydro-power-brief_lr_web.pdf">http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/120228_hydro-power-brief_lr_web.pdf</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref13" name="_edn13">13</a>. Hirsch, P. 2010. ‘The Changing Political Dynamics of Dam Builsing on the Mekong’, Water Alternatives, Vol 3, Issue 2, pp: 312-323, <a href="http://www.water-alternatives.org/index.php/volume3/v3issue2/95-a3-2-18/file">http://www.water-alternatives.org/index.php/volume3/v3issue2/95-a3-2-18/file</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref14" name="_edn14">14</a>. Roberts, D. ‘No More Dams on the Mekong’, New York Times, dated September 23, 2014, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/opinion/no-more-dams-on-the-mekong.html?_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article">http://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/04/opinion/no-more-dams-on-the-mekong.html?_r=0&amp;module=ArrowsNav&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;action=keypress&amp;region=FixedLeft&amp;pgtype=article</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref15" name="_edn15">15</a>. <a href="http://www.stimson.org/images/uploads/research-pdfs/Mekong_Tipping_Point-Complete.pdf">http://www.stimson.org/images/uploads/research-pdfs/Mekong_Tipping_Point-Complete.pdf</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref16" name="_edn16">16</a>. <a href="http://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.cfm?id=12571">http://www.eia.gov/todayinenergy/detail.cfm?id=12571</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref17" name="_edn17">17</a>. Pye, D. ‘Power couple linked to Sinohydro project’, Phnom Penh Post, March 13, 2014, <a href="http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/power-couple-linked-sinohydro-project">http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/power-couple-linked-sinohydro-project</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref18" name="_edn18">18</a>. ‘Agreement on the Cooperation for the Sustainable Development of the Mekong River Basin’, 1995, <a href="http://www.africanwater.org/mekong_comments.htm">http://www.africanwater.org/mekong_comments.htm</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref19" name="_edn19">19</a>. <a href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/news-and-events/news/mrc-holds-special-session-on-prior-consultation-of-don-sahong-hydropower-project/">http://www.mrcmekong.org/news-and-events/news/mrc-holds-special-session-on-prior-consultation-of-don-sahong-hydropower-project/</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref20" name="_edn20">20</a>. <a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/xayaburi-dam">http://www.internationalrivers.org/campaigns/xayaburi-dam</a>\n\n<a href="#_ednref21" name="_edn21">21</a>. <a href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/news-and-events/news/mrc-holds-special-session-on-prior-consultation-of-don-sahong-hydropower-project/">http://www.mrcmekong.org/news-and-events/news/mrc-holds-special-session-on-prior-consultation-of-don-sahong-hydropower-project/</a>\n\nICEM Australia, 2010, ‘MRC Strategic Environmental Assessment (SEA) of hydropower on the Mekong mainstream, Hanoi, Viet Nam, <a href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/Consultations/SEA-Hydropower/SEA-Main-Final-Report.pdf">http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/Consultations/SEA-Hydropower/SEA-Main-Final-Report.pdf</a>\n\n<a href="http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/sea_factsheet_eng.pdf">http://www.internationalrivers.org/files/attached-files/sea_factsheet_eng.pdf</a>\n\n<a href="http://burmariversnetwork.org/index.php/actions/press-releases/1005-ethnic-communities-salween-dams-are-fuelling-war-and-must-be-stopped">http://burmariversnetwork.org/index.php/actions/press-releases/1005-ethnic-communities-salween-dams-are-fuelling-war-and-must-be-stopped</a>\n\nVrieze, P. ‘Optimism and Concern Mark Burma’s First Workshop on Hydropower Dams’, The Irrawaddy, January 23, 2015, <a href="http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/optimism-concern-mark-burmas-first-workshop-hydropower-dams.html">http://www.irrawaddy.org/burma/optimism-concern-mark-burmas-first-workshop-hydropower-dams.html</a>\n\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Hydropower', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'hydropower', '', '', '2015-02-06 10:10:21', '2015-02-06 10:10:21', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=61657', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(61863, 11, '2015-02-09 10:03:03', '2015-02-09 10:03:03', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/flooded-forest.jpeg"><img class="wp-image-69189 size-large" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/flooded-forest-1024x511.jpeg" alt="Flooded forest, Cambodia" width="100%" /></a> Flooded forest, Cambodia. Photograph by Bernard Tey. Cropped.\nLicensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0.</blockquote>\nRivers, lakes, <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/forests-and-forestry/">forests</a> and soil do not exist in separate environments, but are part of ecosystems that interact and support each other. A watershed is the area of land where this interaction takes place. Water from rain, streams and other water bodies run through the land to a common point, such as a bay, a stream channel or a reservoir. A watershed may also be called a catchment or basin.\n\nIn the case of the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">Mekong River</a>, river water flows from the mountains in the Himalayas, down through the basin to the Mekong Delta, and out into the East Vietnam Sea. As it flows, water is also collected from rain run-off, and from the water table beneath the land.\n\nWatersheds are impacted by many factors, through interaction with both natural elements and human activity in the area. The trees and plants in forests not only tap into the water within the soil, but they also affect the quality and composition of the soil itself, filtering rain water and run off as it flows to streams or down into the water table.\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Mekong-watershed-extent-MRC.jpg"><img class="wp-image-69186 size-full" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Mekong-watershed-extent-MRC.jpg" alt="Mekong River profile" width="100%" /></a> Map showing the course and elevation of the Mekong River through five countries<sup><a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1">1</a></sup></blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nSimilarly, <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">agricultural land</a> will affect the composition, chemical balance and quality of the soil, which also impacts the quality and amount of water travelling through the watershed.\n\nLandslides, soil erosion, floods, biodiversity loss, and unsustainable water extraction and farming practices are some of the main reasons for watershed degradation, leading to loss of soil fertility, water tables and springs, as well as desertification and sedimentation<sup><a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2">2</a></sup>.\n\nThe Mekong River Commission was established in 1995 when the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/government/">governments</a> of Cambodia, Laos, Thailand and Vietnam signed the “Mekong Agreement” (<em>Agreement on the Cooperation for the Sustainable Development of the Mekong River Basin</em>). It also provides for the other two countries in the Greater Mekong Subregion (China and Myanmar) to join in cooperative efforts on behalf of the life of the river system.\n\nWhile the agreement does not mention the term “watershed”, it does broadly state its aim as “sustainable development and utilisation of the water and related resources and environment of the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">Mekong River Basin</a>”<sup><a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3">3</a></sup>.\n\nThe Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) has also undertaken assessment and review of its member countries’ watershed management policies and practices, both globally and at regional levels.\n\n[wp-feature-box id="191952"]\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4>References</h4>\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1</a>. Mekong River Commission (1995). <em>Mekong Agreement and Procedures,</em> viii<em>. </em><a title="Mekong Agreement 1995" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/MRC-1995-Agreement-n-procedures.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/MRC-1995-Agreement-n-procedures.pdf</a>. Accessed 29 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2</a>. Krishna Poudel. (2003). Watershed management in Nepal: Challenges and constraints. In (Moujahed Achouri, Larry Tennyson, Kumar Upadhaya &amp; Roger White, Editors) <em>Preparing for the next generation watershed management programmes and projects: Asia.</em> 119-128. <a title="Watershed management in Nepal" href="http://www.fao.org/forestry/11740-029a4d6605fa965edc0fe7a89d8557329.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/forestry/11740-029a4d6605fa965edc0fe7a89d8557329.pdf</a>. Accessed 29 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3</a>. Mekong River Commission (1995). <em>Mekong Agreement and Procedures.</em> <a title="Mekong Agreement 1995" href="http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/MRC-1995-Agreement-n-procedures.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.mrcmekong.org/assets/Publications/policies/MRC-1995-Agreement-n-procedures.pdf</a>. Accessed 29 January 2015.</span><!--:-->', 'Watersheds', '<!--:en-->Watersheds are impacted by many factors, through interaction with both natural elements and human activity in the area. The trees and plants in forests not only tap into the water within the soil, but they also affect the quality and composition of the soil itself, filtering rain water and run off as it flows to streams or down into the water table.<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'watersheds', '', '', '2015-02-09 10:03:03', '2015-02-09 10:03:03', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=61863', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(61864, 11, '2015-04-14 09:11:02', '2015-04-14 09:11:02', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/zoutedrop_Flickr_2008_Thailand-cropped.jpeg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-173718" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/zoutedrop_Flickr_2008_Thailand-cropped-1024x598.jpeg" alt="Mountains around Chiang Mai, Thailand. Photograph by zoutedrop, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0." width="100%" /></a> Mountains around Chiang Mai, Thailand. Photograph by zoutedrop (cropped), Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0.</blockquote>\nThe Lower <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">Mekong Basin</a> is one of the most natural-resource rich and bio-diverse areas in the world. The 4,350 km long Mekong river, which stretches from the Himalayas to the South China Sea, binds together the five Lower Mekong countries (Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam), along with China’s Yunan Province, and provides critical ecosystem services, such as water and biodiversity, to support the region’s growing <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/population-and-census/">population</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economies</a>.\n\nApart from water, the natural resources of the five LMB countries include <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/forests-and-forestry/">forests</a>, wetlands, mangroves, natural <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">fisheries</a> and game, and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/extractive-industries/">minerals and fossil fuels</a> including iron, gold, copper, lead, zinc, tin, silver, gypsum, coal, oil, gas, cement, sand, stone, clay, and precious gems, such as rubies and sapphires. Until recently, its minerals have remained largely untapped.\n\nIts landscape includes mountainous and lowland evergreen forest, deciduous forest, flooded forest, fertile valleys and flood plains, an array of limestone karsts, and the vast Mekong Delta, which stretches from Cambodia’s Tonle Sap to the far southern reaches of Vietnam.\n\nThis wide range of landscapes supports such vast biodiversity that the Mekong basin belongs to one of the world’s biodiversity hotspots ranked in the top five for threat.<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1">1</a> More than 360 new species were discovered in the Greater Mekong Region during 2012 and 2013 alone.<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2">2</a>\n\nThe region’s natural resources are also central to age-old subsistence practices that have provided the region’s forest, farming and fishing communities with their livelihoods.\n\nThe complex hydrology of the Mekong, and its interface with <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/watersheds/">watersheds</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/forests-and-forestry/">forests</a>, provides the water, sedimentation, and organic matter to support almost 15 percent of the world’s paddy <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">rice production</a> in 2014.<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3">3</a> It also makes for the world’s largest freshwater <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">fishery</a>, producing 25 percent of the world’s freshwater catch.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 717px"><a href=''http:&#047;&#047;opendevelopmentmekong.net&#047;briefings&#047;environment-and-natural-resources&#047;''><img alt=''Dashboard 1 '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;IU&#047;IUCNspeciesRedListLMB&#047;Dashboard1&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\n&nbsp;\n\nThe region’s forests produce timber and non-timber forest products—including resins, bamboo, and rattan—that are traded both locally and internationally. In the last 2-3 decades, the rush to modernize and industrialize has significantly altered the Mekong’s landscapes. Although the region’s <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">GDPs</a> have increased substantively as a result, forests declined by 8 million hectares between 1990 and 2010<a style="vertical-align: super" href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4">4</a> (and projected to fall by a further 0.9 percent of the 2010 total by 2020<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5">5</a>) and at least 310 species of fish are now listed as threatened in the five LMB countries.<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6">6</a>\n\nThe development of <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/hydropower/">hydropower</a>, the anticipated expansion of <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/extractive-industries/">mineral extraction</a>, and the transition of agrarian systems to agro-industrial production are set to alter landscapes still further. By 2030 the Mekong basin’s mean temperature is likely to increase by 0.79°C, with greater increases for the colder catchments in the north.<a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7">7</a>\n\nASEAN and the Greater Mekong Subregion countries have nonetheless prioritised environmental protection via programs such as the 2014 <em>Preah Sihanouk Declaration on Building Coastal Resilience to Climate Change Impacts in Southeast Asia</em><a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8">8</a>, and the <em>ASEAN Environmental Education Action Plans</em><a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn9" name="_ednref9">9</a>.\n\nThese and other agreements seek to recognise the potential economic growth in the region, while acknowledging the value of its biodiversity and natural resources.\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177273"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>References</h4>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1.</a> Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund. Indo-Burma Hotspot. <a href="http://www.cepf.net/resources/hotspots/Asia-Pacific/Pages/Indo-Burma.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.cepf.net/resources/hotspots/Asia-Pacific/Pages/Indo-Burma.aspx</a>. Accessed 8 April 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2.</a> World Wide Fund for Nature. Mysterious Mekong: New Species Discoveries 2012-2013. Retrieved from <a href="https://www.worldwildlife.org/publications/mysterious-mekong-new-species-discoveries-2012-2013" target="_blank">https://www.worldwildlife.org/publications/mysterious-mekong-new-species-discoveries-2012-2013</a>.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3.</a> Total 2014 paddy rice production of LMB countries: 104,641,000t; Total global 2014 paddy rice production: 707,480,000 t. World Rice Statistics. <a href="http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs">http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs</a>. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">4.</a> Food And Agriculture Organization Of The United Nations. Forests And Forestry In The Greater Mekong Subregion To 2020. (2011). p. 8. Accessed 21 January 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5.</a> CHEN Erxue, HUANG Kebiao, LI Zengyuan et al. Forest Aboveground Biomass Analysis Using Remote Sensing in the Greater Mekong Subregion, 2011, <em>Resources Science 33</em>(10): 1863-1869.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6.</a> International Union for the Conservation of Nature. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Summary Statistics. <a href="http://cmsdocs.s3.amazonaws.com/summarystats/2014_3_Summary_Stats_Page_Documents/2014_3_RL_Stats_Table_5.pdf">http://cmsdocs.s3.amazonaws.com/summarystats/2014_3_Summary_Stats_Page_Documents/2014_3_RL_Stats_Table_5.pdf</a>. Accessed 3 April 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7.</a> Lebel, L., C.T. Hoanh, C. Krittasudthacheewa, R. Daniel (Eds.) (2014). “Climate risks, regional integration and sustainability in the Mekong region.” SIRD: Kuala Lumpur. <a href="http://www.sumernet.org/content/e-version-sumernet-book-now-available" target="_blank">http://www.sumernet.org/content/e-version-sumernet-book-now-available</a>. Accessed 4 April 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8.</a> International Union for Conservation of Nature. The Preah Sihanouk Declaration on Building Coastal Resilience to Climate Change Impacts in Southeast Asia. (2014). <a href="http://cmsdata.iucn.org/downloads/3rd_coastal_forum__preah_sihanouk_declaration.pdf" target="_blank">http://cmsdata.iucn.org/downloads/3rd_coastal_forum__preah_sihanouk_declaration.pdf</a>. Accessed 2 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref9" name="_edn9">9.</a> ASEAN. Cooperation on Environment. <a href="http://environment.asean.org/action-plans/" target="_blank">http://environment.asean.org/action-plans/</a>. Accessed 1 April 2015.</p>\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Environment and natural resources', '<!--:en-->The region has been heavily reliant on the readily available supplies of forest timber, non-timber forest products and minerals to boost their economies. Various organizations and government agencies are responsible for over-seeing this usage and management, and how they respond to current environmental concerns. <!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'environment-and-natural-resources', '', '', '2015-04-14 09:11:02', '2015-04-14 09:11:02', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=61864', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(61872, 11, '2015-02-09 07:11:58', '2015-02-09 07:11:58', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/MekongFishing_ChristineAndrada3.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-68982" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/MekongFishing_ChristineAndrada3-1024x576.jpg" alt="Mekong River fishing. Photograph by Christine Andrada. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0." width="100%" /></a> Mekong River fishing. Photograph by Christine Andrada. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0.</blockquote>\nThe Lower Mekong Basin (LMB) is moving from largely agrarian fishing and farming countries, to agro-industrial sectors where people farm cash crops rather than those that directly supply their families'' needs. While there are many crops and food products across the LMB, rice and fish still contribute the most to both their <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economies</a> and sustaining their <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/population-and-census/">populations</a>.\n\nThe main crops grown in the LMB include rice, corn (maize), sugar, soy beans, cassava, coffee and rubber. Rubber exports alone accounted for US$19.7 billion in 2011 for the region.<a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1"><sup>1</sup></a>. Following a decline in Brazilian coffee exports, Vietnam was the number one producer of commodity coffee globally in 2014.\n\n<strong>Commodity exports in 2011 (FAO)</strong>\n\n<h6 class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 717px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''LMB Exports 2011 '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;LM&#047;LMBExports2011&#047;LMBExports2011&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></h6>\nThe region has seen a trend towards value-added processing for agricultural and fish products, rather than selling raw materials. Thailand and Vietnam have been doing this for many years with fermented and dried fish for use in the manufacture of products such as sauces and pastes.\n\nThe LMB produced more than 100 million tons of paddy rice in 2014, almost 15 percent of the world total.<a href="#_edn2" name="_ednref2"><sup>2</sup></a> While a large percentage of this rice goes to local trade and within the countries, the region is also a significant exporter of rice to the world. In fact, Laos is the only country of the LMB not to rank in the top ten countries in the world for rice exports. <a href="#_edn3" name="_ednref3"><sup>3</sup></a> This is why the Mekong Basin has been called the “rice bowl of Asia”.\n\n<a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/mekong-river-basin/">The Mekong River system</a> supports the world’s largest inland fishery. Its annual harvest of 2.2 million tonnes of fish has an estimated retail market value between US$4.3 and US$7.8 billion<sup><a href="#_edn4" name="_ednref4">4</a></sup>.\n\nThe River is second only to the Amazon River in the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/environment-and-natural-resources/">biodiversity</a> it supports. The people who live along its banks and within reach of its rich fisheries depend on it as a food source, as it is estimated to supply 75% of people’s protein in some areas<sup><a href="#_edn5" name="_ednref5">5</a></sup>.\n\n<div class=''tableauPlaceholder'' style=''width: 100%;height: 619px''><a href=''#''><img alt=''LMB Fish Production 1950-2010 '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;LM&#047;LMBfishproduction1950-2010&#047;LMBFishProduction1950-2010&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a>  </div>\n\nThe region also has access to significant ocean fisheries in the Andaman Sea, Gulf of Thailand, and South China Sea. Thailand and Vietnam were the number three and four top global exporters of fish and fishery products respectively in 2012, based on value<a href="#_edn6" name="_ednref6"><sup>6</sup></a>.\n\nThe effects of increased use of chemicals, pesticides and fertilizers in intensive farming of crops and aquaculture have not been significantly measured in the region. With the exception of Myanmar, all LMB countries have approved the Rotterdam Convention on the trade and use of pesticides internationally<a href="#_edn7" name="_ednref7"><sup>7</sup></a>, and have government representation for reporting and information sharing. It is unclear, however, what level of pesticide or chemical governance is carried out within those four countries.\n\nAt the 2014 FAO Regional Conference for Asia and the Pacific, representatives from the region committed to achieving the Millennium Development Goal of halving extreme hunger by strengthening policy and reporting around food security. Agricultural reporting from countries across Asia has decreased in quality and quantity over the last decade, and this is seen as a first step towards better food security measures.<sup><a href="#_edn8" name="_ednref8">8</a></sup>\n\n[wp-feature-box id="177279"]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<h4>References</h4>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1</a>. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (2015). Retrieved from <a href="http://faostat3.fao.org/download/T/TP/E" target="_blank">http://faostat3.fao.org/download/T/TP/E</a>. Search terms: Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, 2011, Rubber, natural dry. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref2" name="_edn2">2</a>. Total 2014 paddy rice production of LMB countries: 104,641,000t; Total global 2014 paddy rice production: 707,480,000 t. World Rice Statistics. <a href="http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs">http://ricestat.irri.org:8080/wrs</a>. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref3" name="_edn3">3</a>. US Department of Agriculture; Economic Research Service (2014). Principle rice exporting countries worldwide in 2013 (in 1,000 metric tons of milled equivalent) In <em>USDA - Agricultural Statistics 2013, page I-20</em>. <a href="http://www.statista.com/statistics/255947/top-rice-exporting-countries-worldwide-2011/" target="_blank">http://www.statista.com/statistics/255947/top-rice-exporting-countries-worldwide-2011/</a>. Accessed 6 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref4" name="_edn4">4</a>. Hortle, K.G. (2009) Fisheries of the Mekong river basin. In Campbell, I.C., editor. <em>The Mekong. Biophysical environment of a transboundary river</em>. Elsevier.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref5" name="_edn5">5</a>. Hortle, K.G. (2007) Consumption and the yield of fish and other aquatic animals from the Lower Mekong Basin. <em>MRC Technical Paper No. 16</em>, Mekong River Commission, Vientiane. 87 pp.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref6" name="_edn6">6</a>.Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (2014). <em>The state of world fisheries and aquaculture: Opportunities and challenges</em>. <a href="http://www.fao.org/3/a-i3720e.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/3/a-i3720e.pdf</a>. Accessed 9 February 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref7" name="_edn7">7</a>. United Nations. Rotterdam Convention. <a href="http://www.pic.int/Countries/Statusofratifications/tabid/1072/language/en-US/Default.aspx%23a-note-1">http://www.pic.int/Countries/Statusofratifications/tabid/1072/language/en-US/Default.aspx#a-note-1</a>. Accessed 8 April 2015.</p>\n<p style="font-family: Arial,Verdana;font-size: small"><a href="#_ednref8" name="_edn8">8</a>. Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations. FAO Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific: Strengthening food and nutritional security. <a href="http://www.fao.org/asiapacific/perspectives/food-security/en/" target="_blank">http://www.fao.org/asiapacific/perspectives/food-security/en/</a>. Accessed 9 April 2015.</p><!--:-->', 'Agriculture and fishing', '<!--:en-->The Lower Mekong Basin is moving from largely agrarian fishing and farming countries, to agro-industrial sectors where people farm cash crops rather than those that directly supply their families’ needs. While there are many crops and food products across the LMB, rice and fish still contribute the most to both their economies and to sustaining their populations.<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'agriculture-and-fishing', '', '', '2015-02-09 07:11:58', '2015-02-09 07:11:58', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=61872', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
