(174054, 8, '2015-04-08 10:23:48', '2015-04-08 10:23:48', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8758051143_3c03a52553_k.jpg"><img class="wp-image-174059 size-large" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8758051143_3c03a52553_k-1024x683.jpg" alt="A worker sews a garter to a skirt in a garment factory outside Phnom Penh, Cambodia. Photo by World Bank, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non-Commercial-No-Derivatives 2.0" width="100%" /></a>A worker sews a garter to a skirt in a garment factory outside Phnom Penh, Cambodia. Photo by World Bank, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non-Commercial-No-Derivatives 2.0.</blockquote>\nAccess to suitable and sustainable employment has a direct impact on an individual’s livelihood. In the countries of the Mekong region, even those with education often struggle to secure jobs with fair wages and working conditions. Informal labor, such as a small business operated out of a family home or a day-by-day arrangement with an agricultural company, is a source of income for many who have no reasonable means to enter the professional job market. Generally, there is a correlation between a nation’s employment rate and its level of development, with more developed nations having a higher rate of employment. This trend seems to hold true in the Mekong region as well, according to partial data from the International Labor Organization.\n\nOther issues to be considered within this topic are workers’ rights and migration for work. Employment regulation within countries in the Mekong region are known to generally favour employers'' interests over strong protections for workers, and accurate data on intra-regional labor migration is extremely difficult to source due to the number of migrant workers lacking formal documentation.\n\nThis dynamic may be slowly beginning to shift, however. A notable campaign to increase the minimum wage for garment workers in Cambodia figured prominently in 2013''s national elections. The hazardous working conditions of many factory laborers was also highlighted. The Mekong Migration Network has estimated that there are 3 million migrant workers in the region,<sup><a href="#_edn1">1</a></sup> with Thailand being their most common destination, ever since Thailand’s economic surge in the early 1990s. The organization further noted that much migration in the region is irregular and spontaneous. It is unclear which proportion of these migrants move specifically for employment.\n<h3>References</h3>\n<a href="#_ednref1">1.</a> <a href="http://www.mekongmigration.org/?page_id=25">http://www.mekongmigration.org/?page_id=25</a><!--:-->', 'Labor', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'labor', '', '', '2015-04-08 10:23:48', '2015-04-08 10:23:48', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=174054', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(176713, 8, '2015-04-14 08:42:42', '2015-04-14 08:42:42', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8425021965_440de1adc4_k.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-176715" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8425021965_440de1adc4_k-1024x683.jpg" alt="Photovoltaic cells at Lopburi solar project, Thailand. Photograph: Asian Development Bank, Flickr, 2011. Licensed under Creative Commons Non-Commercial Attribution No-Derivatives 2.0." width="100%" /></a>\n\nPhotovoltaic cells at Lopburi solar project, Thailand. Photograph: Asian Development Bank, Flickr, 2011. Licensed under Creative Commons Non-Commercial Attribution No-Derivatives 2.0.</blockquote>\nThe demand for energy in South East Asia has increased by two-and-a-half times the global average since 1990, making it one of the most rapid growth rates in the world<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup>. In the context of rising energy demands of the industrial sector, and household electricity demand thanks to increased urbanization, these developments have huge implications for the energy trade and energy security of the five countries of the Lower Mekong Basin. A stable supply of clean, efficient, and cost effective energy is fundamental to sustainable <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economic growth</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">development</a> in the region.\n\nWhile energy markets across the Lower Mekong Region vary from country to country in terms of energy demand and production capacity, there has been rapid development in the LMB energy sector over the past two decades—such as the roll-out of rural electricity access—it has primarily followed national agendas, and contributed little to regional connectedness. Thus, access to energy resources and power generation remains unevenly distributed across the region, and has contributed to a mutual import-export dependency among LMB countries.\n\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 802px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''Final energy consumption 2000-2012 '' src=''https://public.tableau.com/static/images/Fi/Finalenergyconsumption2001-2012CambodiaMyanmarVietnamThailandLaoPDR/Finalenergyconsumption2000-2012CambodiaMyanmarVietnamThailandLaoPDR/1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\n\nIn terms of power trade flows in the region, Laos is the largest volume exporter and the most competitively priced supplier. Thailand and Vietnam are reliant on imports from Laos, Cambodia and Myanmar to meet their rapidly growing electricity demands, particularly from <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/hydropower/">hydropower</a> generation. Due to Cambodia’s exorbitant domestic electricity prices, it too relies on imports from its neighbours rather than its own power production<sup><a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">2</a></sup>. Fossil fuels play a large role in the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/economy-and-commerce/">economies</a> of the LMB countries and will continue to in the future, with coal, oil and gas resources supporting the growth in energy demand. Fossil-fuels remain the major energy source in the region, with the demand for coal projected to overtake natural gas and rise sharply to 28% of the primary energy mix by 2035<sup><a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3">3</a></sup>. This would represent nearly one-fifth of the global growth in demand for coal. The domestic demand for fossil fuels is such that the region will face an increase in reliance on fuel imports. In 2011 alone, Thailand’s net oil and gas imports totaled $30 billion, and are projected to reach $100 billion in 2035. Vietnam has the second-largest coal reserves in the region with 3.1 billion tonnes of hard coal and 0.2 billion tonnes of brown coal. Meanwhile, what Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar lack in <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/extractive-industries/">fossil fuel deposits</a>, they make up in renewable and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/hydropower/">hydropower</a> energy potential. Laos plans to increase its share of renewables by 30 percent by 2025, which includes a 10 percent target for using biofuels in transport. Myanmar intends to increase its share of renewable power generating capacity to 18 percent of its energy mix by 2020. Biomass has huge potential in Cambodia as its low levels of rural electrification make it the main energy source for millions of Cambodians – up to 85% - who rely on wood and charcoal for domestic cooking, but not for power generation<sup><a href="#_ftn4" name="_ftnref4">4</a></sup>. Several regional energy initiatives exist, primarily aimed at energy market integration and cooperation on energy security and sustainability. The five countries of the LMB generally fall under broader regional definitions under the Asian Development Bank’s Greater Mekong Subregion Program, and ASEAN’s various energy bodies under the intra-governmental ASEAN Energy Centre. [wp-feature-box id="177280"]   \n\n<h4> References</h4>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1]</a> IEA, “Southeast Asia Energy Outlook: Special report”, World Energy Outlook, October 2, 2014, accessed February, 2015 <a href="http://www.worldenergyoutlook.org/southeastasiaenergyoutlook/#d.en.43468">http://www.worldenergyoutlook.org/southeastasiaenergyoutlook/#d.en.43468</a></span> <span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> June, A. “Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS) Market Coordination.”Paper presented at the Sustainable Energy Training, Bangkok, Thailand, November 27, 2013. <a href="http://www.iea.org/media/training/bangkoknov13/session_9a_adb_gms_regional_market.pdf">http://www.iea.org/media/training/bangkoknov13/session_9a_adb_gms_regional_market.pdf</a></span> <span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3">[3]</a> IEA “Southeast Asia Energy Outlook” pg. 69</span> <span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4">[4]</a> “Cambodia Energy Situation,” Energypedia, accessed April 8, 2015. https://energypedia.info/wiki/Cambodia_Energy_Situation#Major_Energy_Challenges</span> <span style="font-size: 10pt">ASEAN Centre for Energy, accessed April 4, 2015<a href="http://www.aseanenergy.org/">  http://www.aseanenergy.org/</a></span> <span style="font-size: 10pt">Asian Development Bank, Energy portal, accessed April 4, 2015<a href="http://www.adb.org/sectors/energy/main"> http://www.adb.org/sectors/energy/main</a></span> <span style="font-size: 10pt">Lucas, N. "Energy Security for Asia: Prospects for Regional Cooperation," Asian Development Bank, published September, 2014, accessed April 5, 2015<a href="http://www.adb.org/publications/energy-security-asia-prospects-regional-cooperation"> http://www.adb.org/publications/energy-security-asia-prospects-regional-cooperation</a></span> <span style="font-size: 10pt"> </span><!--:-->', 'Energy', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'energy', '', '', '2015-04-14 08:42:42', '2015-04-14 08:42:42', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=176713', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(176716, 11, '2015-04-14 09:05:09', '2015-04-14 09:05:09', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/4928585291_a261737f61_o.jpg"><img class="size-full wp-image-177285" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/4928585291_a261737f61_o.jpg" alt="Photo by Richard Cawood, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0." width="100%" /></a> Photo by Richard Cawood, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Non Commercial 2.0.</blockquote>\nThe economies of the five LMB countries range from those still developing beyond a reliance on <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/agriculture-and-fishing/">agriculture</a> and <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/environment-and-natural-resources/">natural resources</a>, to more robust export economies supporting themselves and becoming more independent.\n\nFor the 2015 fiscal year, the World Bank categorized the region''s economies as "low-income" (Cambodia and Myanmar), "lower-middle-income" (Laos and Vietnam) and "upper-middle-income" (Thailand).<a href="#refs"><sup>1</sup></a>\n\nApart from Thailand, which commenced repaying its development loans on 2000, the <a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">other economies in the region are dependent on outside aid, and development funding</a> and partnerships. Myanmar''s economy has had greater exposure to overseas funds since its former military government announced moves towards more democratic processes in 2012, lifting long-standing embargoes on trade from Western governments.\n\nThe total gross domestic product (GDP) of all five countries in the <abbr title="Lower Mekong Basin">LMB</abbr> was US$677.6 billion in 2013 according to United Nations'' data.<a href="#refs"><sup>2</sup></a> While recent variances in population reporting for Myanmar make GDP per capita figures unreliable, the average for the other four countries in the region in 2013 was US$2,684 (nominal).<a href="#refs"><sup>3</sup></a>\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 469px"><a href=''http:&#047;&#047;opendevelopmentmekong.net&#047;briefings&#047;economy-and-commerce&#047;''><img alt=''2013 LMB GDP '' src=''https:&#047;&#047;public.tableau.com&#047;static&#047;images&#047;LM&#047;LMBGDP2013&#047;2013LMBGDP&#047;1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\nWith the exception of Vietnam, all countries in the LMB had a current account deficit at the end of 2013, according to the Asian Development Bank. This measures the difference between a country''s savings and its investments. Vietnam''s current account balance increased each year from 2010 to 2013, while all other LMB countries'' balances decreased.\n\nMeasured as a percentage of Gross Domestic Product (GDP), the average current account balance of the LMB is -7.8 percent of GDP, ranging from -29.5 percent for Laos to 6.5 percent for Vietnam. Total merchandise exports from the LMB grew more than three-fold in the ten years from 2004 to 2013 (2004: US$128.47 billion; 2013: US$382.66 billion).\n\nWhile the overall picture for the LMB is one of potential growth and foreign investment opportunities, individual scenarios in some countries — e.g., Myanmar''s internal conflicts with rebel military groups, Thailand''s military coups, and Vietnam''s territorial dispute with China — have caused investor confidence to fluctuate in recent years.\n\nMyanmar is eager to capitalize on the new trade freedom it has experienced since 2012. The government has set goals to increase sectors such as tourism, infrastructure and foreign investment, however continuing sectarian violence and domestic conflict in the country is still a concern for tourists and investors alike.\n\nTourism revenue is important to the economies of several LMB countries, especially Cambodia (13.5% of 2014 GDP), Thailand (8.6% of 2014 GDP) and Laos (5% of 2014 GDP), and is an increasing contributor for Myanmar. Thailand''s 2013 military coup saw its number of tourist arrivals, and resulting revenue, drop. There has been an increase in tourism for other countries in the region over that same period, however the table below suggests that this is not due to tourists choosing other LMB destinations over Thailand.\n\nThe region''s<a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/infrastructure/"> transport investment</a> priority was highlighted in the <em>Greater Mekong Subregion Economic Cooperation Program Strategic Framework for 2012-2022</em>, developed by representatives of China and the five nations of the LMB in 2011. It identified 92 projects costing an estimated US$30 billion, 90% of which are transport sector projects.<sup><a href="#refs">4</a></sup>\n\nYou can read more about the levels of official development assistance for each country on the <a title="Aid and development in the Lower Mekong Basin" href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/topics/aid-and-development-assistance/">Aid and development page</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n<a name="refs"></a>\n<h4>References</h4>\n<span style="font-size: 10pt;font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif">1. The World Bank. "Country and Lending Groups." 2015. <a href="http://data.worldbank.org/about/country-and-lending-groups">http://data.worldbank.org/about/country-and-lending-groups</a>. Accessed 9 April 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt;font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif">2. United Nations Statistics Division. "GDP and its breakdown at current prices in US Dollars". December 2014.<a href="http://unstats.un.org/unsd/snaama/dnltransfer.asp?fID=2" target="_blank">href="http://unstats.un.org/unsd/snaama/dnltransfer.asp?fID=2</a>. Accessed 6 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-size: 10pt;font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif">3. United Nations Statistics Division. National Accounts Main Aggregates Database, December 2013. <a href="http://unstats.un.org/unsd/snaama/selbasicFast.asp">http://unstats.un.org/unsd/snaama/selbasicFast.asp</a>. Accessed on 4 January 2015.</span>\n\n<span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;font-size: 10pt">4. Asian Development Bank. "The Greater Mekong Subregion Economic Cooperation Program Strategic Framework (2012-2022)". <a href="http://www.adb.org/documents/greater-mekong-subregion-economic-cooperation-program-strategic-framework-2012-2022" target="_blank">http://www.adb.org/documents/greater-mekong-subregion-economic-cooperation-program-strategic-framework-2012-2022</a>. Accessed 30 March 2015.</span><!--:-->', 'Economy and commerce', '<!--:en-->The economies of the five LMB countries range from those still developing beyond a reliance on agriculture and natural resources, to more robust export economies supporting themselves and becoming more independent. For the 2015 fiscal year, the World Bank categorized the region’s economies as “low-income” (Cambodia and Myanmar), “lower-middle-income” (Laos and Vietnam) and “upper-middle-income” (Thailand).<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'economy-and-commerce', '', '', '2015-04-14 09:05:09', '2015-04-14 09:05:09', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=176716', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(176906, 10, '2015-04-09 10:18:51', '2015-04-09 10:18:51', '<!--:en--><blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8787492788_b36276f547_k.jpg"><img class="size-large wp-image-176905" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/8787492788_b36276f547_k-1024x683.jpg" alt="Primary school students in Oudomxay province, Lao by World Bank, 2012. Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic" width="100%" height="100%" /></a>\n\nPrimary school students in Oudomxay province, Lao by World Bank, 2012. Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivs 2.0 Generic.</blockquote>\n&nbsp;\n\nOver the last two decades, the countries of the Lower Mekong Basin (LMB) have all experienced economic development and social transformation. While development remains unequal between a fledgling low-income, developing economy like Myanmar compared to a high-income, developed country like Thailand, the now middle-income countries Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam are considered development success stories due to the improvements they have made in less than one generation <a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1"><sup>1</sup></a>. However, while these results are encouraging over all, the multidimensional nature of measuring social development progress means that improvements across indicators are not always equal, and that as the disparity between the growing urban classes and rural poor increases, and demographic changes continue, inequality in the region must still be addressed.\n\nThe Copenhagen Declaration on Social Development defines social development as an approach that addresses the “profound social problems, especially poverty, unemployment and social exclusion, that affect every country"<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2"><sup>2</sup></a>. Not simply linked to economic development, social development is measured by a range of indicators including average life expectancy, water supply and sanitation coverage, literacy rates, and issues of gender and social exclusion affecting the disadvantaged and ethnic minorities. In this way, poverty is defined beyond income levels and is viewed across a spectrum of social and structural barriers.\n\nIn a global context, the LMB region has outpaced other developing regions, with Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam tying for second place in an assessment <a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3"><sup>3</sup></a> of each country’s progress towards the <a href="http://www.un.org/millenniumgoals/">Millennium Development Goals</a>. Similarly, each country in the LMB improved its Human Development Index ranking over the period 1980-2013 <a href="#_ftn4" name="_ftnref4"><sup>4</sup></a>.\n\n\n<div class="tableauPlaceholder" style="width: 100%;height: 802px"><a href=''#''><img alt=''Human Development Index 1980-2013 '' src=''https://public.tableau.com/static/images/Hu/HumanDevelopmentIndex1980-2013/Dashboard1/1_rss.png'' style=''border: none'' /></a></div>\n&nbsp;\n\nIn the case of Vietnam, which in 1993 had a poverty rate of 58%, improvements in health, education, efforts to reach gender parity and provide safety nets for disadvantaged groups, has earned it much praise. Today the poverty rate is less than 15 per cent <a href="#_ftn5" name="_ftnref5"><sup>5</sup></a>.\nLaos too has reduced the proportion of people living under the poverty line by 40% since 1993, and has made great strides towards universal primary education coverage and reducing the under 5 mortality rate. However, despite reaching the MDG targets, child mortality remains the highest in the region and the average life expectancy is as low as 68.31 years. Over 36% of Lao’s population lives in multidimensional poverty, compared to Thailand’s 1.01% which largely represents its rural poor <a href="#_ftn6" name="_ftnref6"><sup>6</sup></a>.\nMyanmar lags behind it’s LMB neighbors, and is off-track to meet the MDG target to eradicate extreme poverty and hunger until 2025<a href="#_ftn7" name="_ftnref7"><sup>7</sup></a>. The lack of reliable data available in Myanmar, which is either nonexistent or contains large gaps, makes statistical analysis difficult. For instance, there remains uncertainty about the true size of the country’s population<a href="#_ftn8" name="_ftnref8"> <sup>8</sup></a>.\n\nWhile poverty reduction has been overwhelmingly successful over the past 2 decades, and a successful MDG target for the Asia-Pacific region (reducing the number of people living on less than $1.25 a day from 50 to 20 per cent), significant gaps in social development indicators remain. Poor quality health and education, particularly for the rural poor, remains “unfinished business”<a href="#_ftn9" name="_ftnref9"><sup>9</sup></a> in all LMB countries, as does a lack of secure jobs for the region’s vulnerable workers. Sustained effort towards environmental management and conservation is also seriously lacking as unplanned urbanization and pressure on natural resources continues to increase.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h4> References</h4>\n<a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">[1] </a><span style="font-size: 10pt">Barmeier, L. &amp; Leo, B. (2010) Who Are the MDG Trailblazers? A New MDG Progress Index, <em>Working Paper 222</em>, Centre for Global Development, Retrieved from <a href="http://www.cgdev.org/publication/who-are-mdg-trailblazers-new-mdg-progress-index-working-paper-222">http://www.cgdev.org/publication/who-are-mdg-trailblazers-new-mdg-progress-index-working-paper-222</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">[2]</a> <span style="font-size: 10pt">Copenhagen Declaration on Social Development, 1995. Retrieved from<span style="text-decoration: underline">  </span><a href="http://www.un.org/esa/socdev/wssd/text-version/agreements/decparti.htm">http://www.un.org/esa/socdev/wssd/text-version/agreements/decparti.htm</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3">[3]</a> <span style="font-size: 10pt">Brooke Lewis, "Cambodia hailed over UN targets", <em>The Phnom Penh Post,</em> September 6, 2010, accessed April 8, 2015 <a href="http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/cambodia-hailed-over-un-targets">http://www.phnompenhpost.com/national/cambodia-hailed-over-un-targets</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref5" name="_ftn5">[5] </a><span style="font-size: 10pt">Caitlin Kelley, "Spotlight On: Vietnam", <em>Impact</em>, University of Nottingham, March 20, 2015, accessed on April 8, 2015 <a href="http://www.impactnottingham.com/2015/03/spotlight-on-vietnam/">http://www.impactnottingham.com/2015/03/spotlight-on-vietnam/</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref6" name="_ftn6">[6]</a> <span style="font-size: 10pt">United Nations (2015), <em>Millennium Development Indicators: Country and Regional Progress Snapshots, </em>Retrieved on April 7, 2015 <a href="http://hdr.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/THA">http://hdr.undp.org/en/countries/profiles/THA</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref7" name="_ftn7">[7] </a><span style="font-size: 10pt">MDG Track (2011-2015), <em>Monitoring Progress Towards the Millennium Development Goals</em>, Tac Economics, Retrieved April 5, 2015</span><span style="font-size: 10pt"> <a href="http://www.mdgtrack.org/index.php?tab=c&amp;c=MMR">http://www.mdgtrack.org/index.php?tab=c&amp;c=MMR</a></span>\n\n<a href="#_ftnref9" name="_ftn9">[9]</a> <span style="font-size: 10pt">UNDP (2013), "Asia-Pacific Aspirations: Perspectives for a Post-2015 Development Agenda", Asia-Pacific Regional MDGs Report 2012/13. Retrieved on April 8, 2015  <a href="http://www.undp.org/content/dam/undp/library/MDG/english/MDG%20Regional%20Reports/AP/RBAP-RMDG-Report-2012-2013.pdf">http://www.undp.org/content/dam/undp/library/MDG/english/MDG%20Regional%20Reports/AP/RBAP-RMDG-Report-2012-2013.pdf</a></span>\n\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Social development', '<!--:en-->Over the last two decades, the countries of the Lower Mekong Basin have all experienced economic development and social transformation. While results are encouraging over all, the improvements across development indicators are not always equal, and as the disparity between the growing urban classes and rural poor increases, and demographic changes continue, inequality in the region still must be addressed.<!--:-->', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'social-development', '', '', '2015-04-09 10:18:51', '2015-04-09 10:18:51', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=176906', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
(177081, 8, '2015-04-09 10:26:22', '2015-04-09 10:26:22', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><img class="size-large wp-image-177083" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/6839221170_da1cb719ec_k-1024x769.jpg" alt="Presidential palace, Vientiane, Laos. Photograph: caflier002, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Share-Alike 2.0." width="760" height="571" /> Presidential palace, Vientiane, Laos. Photograph: caflier002, Flickr. Licensed under Creative Commons Share-Alike 2.0.</blockquote>\nThere are three types of government in the Mekong region:\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>Thailand and Cambodia operate as constitutional monarchies, allowing for royalty and a parliamentary body to coexist.</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Laos and Vietnam are single-party socialist republics.</strong></li>\n	<li><strong>Myanmar’s government is a unitary presidential constitutional republic.</strong></li>\n</ol>\nAfter decades under military rule, Myanmar became a partially civilian government in 2011, allowing increased trade and investment. One of its government’s biggest challenges is the ongoing conflict between ethnic groups in the country.\n\nThailand has experienced many coups throughout the past 80 years, in which the military took control of the government. The most recent case was in 2014, and a former commander-in-chief of the Royal Thai Army is now the country’s prime minister. This has strained relations with other countries, and international organizations have called for a return to democratic rule. In spite of this uncertain climate, the effects on tourism and day-to-day business seemed relatively small, although some analysts predict a negative impact<sup><a style="vertical-align: super;font-size: small" href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1">1</a></sup> on the Thai economy in the long-term.\n\nIn 2013, Cambodia had one of its most contested national elections in modern history. Mass rallies of opposition party supporters led to occasionally violent clashes with police. After a standoff of over a year, the opposition party took up its seats in the national assembly in 2014. January 2015 was the 30<sup>th</sup> anniversary of Prime Minister Hun Sen coming to that role.\n\nAs single-party states, Vietnam and Laos have had relative stability.\n\nOverall, the governments of Mekong nations have been recognized as legitimate by the United Nations since the mid-1900s, and diplomatic relations between Mekong nations and other countries is affirmed by the presence of numerous embassies. However, concerns about government corruption and human rights abuses persist throughout the region.\n<h4> References</h4>\n<span style="font-size: 10pt"><a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1">1.</a><em>Thailand''s Economy: The high cost of stability</em>, The Economist, published October 8, 2014. Accessed April 8, 2015. <a href="http://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2014/10/thailands-economy">http://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2014/10/thailands-economy</a></span><!--:-->', 'Government', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'government', '', '', '2015-04-09 10:26:22', '2015-04-09 10:26:22', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=177081', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
