(177457, 8, '2015-04-09 11:54:48', '2015-04-09 11:54:48', '<!--:en--><em><strong>This page is under development, with additions and updates forthcoming.</strong></em>\n<blockquote><a href="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/10482389655_4eba3c22e3_o.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-large wp-image-177460" src="http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/10482389655_4eba3c22e3_o-1024x678.jpg" alt="10482389655_4eba3c22e3_o" width="760" height="503" /></a>\nA night market in Vietnam. Photgraph: Podoboq, Flickr, 2013. Licensed under Creative Commons Attribution 2.0.</blockquote>\nAlthough the Mekong region can be considered as a defined geographic area, it is not a homogenous entity. There is wide variety among the cultures and subcultures of each of the five nations, with numerous ethnic groups, religious beliefs, and other demographic differences. Historically, Southeast Asia was a crossroads between the powerful influences of India and China. This is still reflected in Mekong societies, as is the legacy of French colonial rule in Vietnam, Laos, and Cambodia. However, collectivism and traditionally-held Buddhist values are common ties. The majority of the population is rural and engaged in subsistence farming, although urbanization is occurring at varying rates in all five countries.\n\nThe youth population in Mekong nations ranges from 30 percent to more than 50 percent, as estimated by the CIA World Factbook.<sup><a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1">1</a></sup> This suggests a significant shift in the future governance of the region, as young people are often more willing to engage with new movements and technologies. The younger generation’s coming of age has implications for all other sectors of development, especially labor, the economy, and natural resource management.\n\nCensus-taking is not uniform in such a diverse region with large rural areas. Although national governments have attempted to collect data from representative samples of their populations, inconsistencies remain. With the exception of Myanmar, each country in the region has at least semi-regularly performed a population census in the past 20 years, with some of this data available online. A UN-supported census<sup><a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2">2</a></sup> was conducted in 2014 in Myanmar, its first in 30 years.\n<h4> References</h4>\n<a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1">1.</a> <a href="https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2010.html">https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2010.html</a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2">2.</a> <a href="http://countryoffice.unfpa.org/myanmar/census/">http://countryoffice.unfpa.org/myanmar/census/</a>\n\n&nbsp;<!--:-->', 'Population and census', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'population-and-census', '', '', '2015-04-09 11:54:48', '2015-04-09 11:54:48', '', 0, 'http://opendevelopmentmekong.net/?post_type=briefing&amp;p=177457', 0, 'topic', '', 0),
